
[1]viviparous

   VIVIP'AROUS, a. [L. vivus, alive, and pario, to bear.]

   1. Producing young in a living state, as all mammifers; as
   distinguished from oviparous, producing eggs, as fowls. If fowls were
   viviparous, it is difficult to how the female would fly during
   preganancy.

   2. In botany, producing its offspring alive, either by bulbs instead of
   seeds, or by the seeds themselves germinating on the plant, instread of
   falling, as they usually do; as a viviparous plant.
